
@startuml
' Class Diagram for Louvre Museum Exhibition Management System

class Museum {
  -name: String
  -locations: List<Location>
}

class Location {
  -name: String
  -exhibitions: List<Exhibition>
}

class Exhibition {
  -title: String
  -startDate: Date
  -endDate: Date
  -coordinator: Employee
  -items: List<ExhibitionItem>
}

class Employee {
  -name: String
  -role: String
  -coach: Employee
}

class ExhibitionItem {
  -description: String
  -pieces: List<Piece>
}

class Piece {
  -title: String
  -artist: String
  -collector: Collector
}

class Collector {
  -name: String
  -pieces: List<Piece>
}

' Relationships

Museum "1" --> "0..*" Location
Location "1" --> "0..*" Exhibition
Exhibition "1" --> "1" Employee : coordinator
Employee "1" --> "0..1" Employee : coach
Exhibition "1" --> "0..*" ExhibitionItem
ExhibitionItem "1" --> "0..*" Piece
Piece "1" --> "1" Collector

@enduml

---

### Explanation of Classes and Relationships:

- **Museum**: Contains multiple `Location`s.
- **Location**: Can host multiple `Exhibition`s.
- **Exhibition**: Has a start and end date, a coordinator (`Employee`), and a list of `ExhibitionItem`s.
- **Employee**: Each has a name, role, and potentially a `Coach` (another `Employee`).
- **ExhibitionItem**: Represents an item needed in an exhibition. It can be fulfilled by one or more `Piece`s.
- **Piece**: A specific artwork, with an artist and associated `Collector`.
- **Collector**: Owns multiple `Piece`s.

This model supports tracking exhibitions, their planning stages, required items, sourcing from collectors, and the coaching relationships between employees.